body:
I have this proc-macro crate containing a function-like proc macro and a derive macro, both of which just print their input tokens in debug form. The function-like macro expands to `0`. The derive macro expands to nothing.

```rust
extern crate proc_macro;
use proc_macro::TokenStream;

#[proc_macro]
pub fn zero(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    println!("ZERO: {:#?}", input);
    "0".parse().unwrap()
}

#[proc_macro_derive(Derive)]
pub fn derive(input: TokenStream) -> TokenStream {
    println!("DERIVE: {:#?}", input);
    TokenStream::new()
}
```

When I mix these proc macros with macro_rules metavariables I see strange and broken-seeming behavior. Note that I am using `proc_macro_hygiene` here because it is the most concise way to demonstrate the problem, but the same problem exists on stable.

```rust
#![feature(proc_macro_hygiene)]

extern crate print;

macro_rules! m {
    ($e:expr) => {
        #[derive(print::Derive)]
        struct _S([u8; print::zero!(2 * $e)]);
    };
}

m!(1 + 1);
```

I would expect the equivalent of `2 * (1 + 1)` in the debug print of both macro invocations, except with the delimiter around `1 + 1` being None instead of parentheses.

Indeed the output from `print::zero` is what I would expect.

```rust
ZERO: TokenStream [
    Literal {
        lit: Integer(
            2
        ),
        suffix: None,
        span: #2 bytes(159..160)
    },
    Punct {
        ch: '*',
        spacing: Alone,
        span: #2 bytes(161..162)
    },
    Group {
        delimiter: None,
        stream: TokenStream [
            Literal {
                lit: Integer(
                    1
                ),
                suffix: None,
                span: #2 bytes(163..165)
            },
            Punct {
                ch: '+',
                spacing: Alone,
                span: #2 bytes(163..165)
            },
            Literal {
                lit: Integer(
                    1
                ),
                suffix: None,
                span: #2 bytes(163..165)
            }
        ],
        span: #2 bytes(163..165)
    }
]
```

But the output from `print::Derive` is missing the None-delimited group around `1 + 1`, resulting in the wrong precedence when parsing this token stream.

```rust
/* ... */
Ident {
    ident: "zero",
    span: #0 bytes(0..0)
},
Punct {
    ch: '!',
    spacing: Alone,
    span: #0 bytes(0..0)
},
Group {
    delimiter: Parenthesis,
    stream: TokenStream [
        Literal {
            lit: Integer(
                2
            ),
            suffix: None,
            span: #0 bytes(0..0)
        },
        Punct {
            ch: '*',
            spacing: Alone,
            span: #0 bytes(0..0)
        },
        Literal {
            lit: Integer(
                1
            ),
            suffix: None,
            span: #0 bytes(0..0)
        },
        Punct {
            ch: '+',
            spacing: Alone,
            span: #0 bytes(0..0)
        },
        Literal {
            lit: Integer(
                1
            ),
            suffix: None,
            span: #0 bytes(0..0)
        }
    ],
    span: #0 bytes(0..0)
}
/* ... */
```

This is with rustc 1.31.0-nightly (1cf82fd9c 2018-10-30).

Mentioning @eddyb, @alexcrichton.
